fields.descriptive_line: A group of Burmese manuscript artifacts all from the era of the Konbaung Dynasty (1752-1885) and probably 19th century.  A royal abeydamma (Burmese Buddhist canonical manuscript) of stiffened cloth; in Pali with small Burmese square script; gilded red lacquer decorated with a lotus leaf pattern. A pair of unrelated red lacquered wood Kyan (binding boards) with floral and lotus motifs. A woven cotton zig-zag patterned binding ribbon.
fields.physical_description:
[Binding ribbon] A sa-si-gyo (manuscript binding ribbon).
Cotton.
Example of tablet or card weaving;
inter-woven with zig-zag pattern.
[Manuscript cover] See IS 46 - 1981
[Manuscript cover] A pair (with IS 46A-1981) of shaped heavy wood kyan (binding boards);  bright red lacquered.
Outside: 4 medallions with lotus and floral motifs.
Inside: 2 different titles of text: anusayayamuik palito and thragatha path tatiya thup (text no longer represented in this manuscript)
[Manuscript page] <font -u>IS 46:1 to 59 - 1981</font>  

Fragment of the Abeydamma - one of the "three baskets" of the Tripitaka. Compendium of philosophy of the Buddhist doctrine.
59 folios with 2 cord holes decorated with 2 concentric circles.
8 lines, 54 char., Pali (a classical language in the East comparable to classical Greek and Latin in the West), small Burmese square script in black lacquer.
Paginated with square Burmese letters.
Margins: (4 cm) Decorated with a repeating lotus leaf pattern in red lacquer. 
Title (in red in the margin) on each page on the verso right hand upper corner.

fields.name: South and South East Asian Collection

fields.marks: [Manuscript cover] Label pasted inside with "No. 2868 - Burmese Ms. on palm leaves  papier-mache. £7.10.0".
fields.production_note: Attribution note: These are the middle pages only of a much larger work which is typical as one is unlikely to find a complete manuscript of this type, leaves being scattered in many repositories. It's origins maybe royal but there are no end pages which would have given the name of the King for which it was written and the date. Opinion of Mme. Jacqueline Filliozat, Bibliotheque National, Paris, 1996.
